7. STACK DEPLOY (1st pass) — FOREGROUND-WARMUP TRAP
================================================================================

Used /deploy-stack skill against the same parameter block as the
2026-04-26 deploy. Stack went UPDATE_COMPLETE; CEs forced to refresh
via update-compute-environment with updateToLatestImageVersion=true;
both spot + on-demand back to ENABLED + VALID.

Resumed I16 max005 under screen `nf` with project name
max005-20260427-203146. Cached upstream stages (AWS_DOWNLOAD,
get_software_versions) hit; FASTERQ_DUMP queued 5 jobs RUNNABLE.

Then: nothing. For ~50 minutes, two workers (i-031fa1854fa999308 +
i-0edf0c9ddd29ccdbd) were "running" in EC2 but ECS never registered
them. Couldn't SSM in (TargetNotConnected), implying SSM agent
hadn't started. Both workers were eventually spot-reclaimed before
finishing whatever they were doing.

Replacement worker i-08970c1fc7dda1793 launched 00:19 UTC the next
day, same problem: 50+ min in, ECS still didn't see it. Console
output via aws ec2 get-console-output cracked the case:

  [   76]  cloud-init: + cat /mnt/dbs/metaphlan_databases/vJan25/*.bt2l
  ... no further output until 3670 sec later ...
  [ 3670]  systemd-shutdown[1]: Powering off.

The UserData warmup was running in the FOREGROUND. cloud-init
blocked behind the cat for the full lazy-load window. SSM agent
and ECS agent both depend on cloud-init completion before
registering, so the worker accepted no jobs. Spot reclamation
killed it after ~61 min — before the warmup even finished — and
Batch spawned a replacement that hit the same wall. Endless cycle.

================================================================================
8. SNAPSHOT LAZY-LOAD DISCOVERY — REVISED I20 + I23, NEW I24
================================================================================

Live observation during the stuck UserData: cat read rate was
~6 MB/s (7 GB loaded after ~20 min). At that rate the 34 GB index
takes ~95 min to fully read.

This is far below the 125 MB/s gp3 baseline that I20 originally
predicted. Investigation: this is **EBS snapshot lazy-load**, not
gp3 throughput. Two distinct layers were conflated:

  - gp3 user throughput: 125 MB/s baseline, configurable up to
    1000 MB/s. Applies to the steady-state volume AFTER init.
  - Snapshot lazy-load: separate upstream throttle. First-touch
    reads pull blocks from S3 to EBS at ~6-50 MB/s regardless
    of gp3 settings. Lasts until every block has been read once.

Bumping gp3 throughput/IOPS does nothing for first-boot warmup.
The original I23 plan (250 / 500 MB/s throughput, ~$5-15/month)
was based on a layer that doesn't apply to fresh workers.

The custom AMI from I14 didn't eliminate the slow-first-read
problem; it relocated it from `aws s3 sync` (visible) to snapshot
lazy-load (invisible). Total cost-per-fresh-worker is similar.

Three artifacts (commit 883ef8f):

  - I24 (new) — Enable EBS Fast Snapshot Restore on the worker
    AMI snapshot. Pre-replicates per-AZ; volumes restored from a
    FSR-enabled snapshot serve full gp3 throughput from boot.
    Cost ~$0.75/AZ/hr × 3 AZ = $2.25/hr while enabled.
    Comparable to a network-FS subscription but pay-as-you-go;
    enable just before a big run, disable after.

  - I20 (revised) — caveat at top: warmup math (5 min for 34 GB)
    assumes post-init or FSR; on fresh workers expect 30-90 min
    UserData blocking. Pre-warm is still useful (puts the cost
    in boot phase, amortizes over many tasks per worker), but
    only delivers when paired with I24 OR worker reuse.

  - I23 (revised) — rescoped to post-init only. New table at top
    mapping each disk-activity phase to its actual bottleneck.

================================================================================
9. WARMUP-BACKGROUNDING FIX — UNBLOCKED THE RUN
================================================================================

Root-cause fix (commit 56a0c98): wrap the cat in nohup ... & in
batch-stack.yaml UserData so cloud-init returns immediately. ECS
agent then registers within ~1 min and accepts jobs while the
warmup hydrates the volume in the background. Output of the
warmup (with `time`) appended to /var/log/nf-userdata.log so we
can still measure how long the lazy-load actually takes.

Before:
  [   76]  cloud-init: + cat /mnt/dbs/.../vJan25/*.bt2l
  [ 3670]  systemd-shutdown: Powering off  (cloud-init never
                                            finished; SSM never
                                            registered)

After (commit 56a0c98 + redeploy):
  [   76]  cloud-init: + nohup bash -c 'time cat ...'
  [   76]  cloud-init: + echo 'worker boot done'
  [   76]  Cloud-init finished. Up 76.12 seconds
  [   82]  Amazon SSM Agent v3.3.4108 is running
  [  158]  ECS container instance ACTIVE (Tasks=4)

Worker i-0c55871f5b0313baa (m8g.2xlarge, launched 16:27:41 UTC):
  16:29:06  cloud-init exit
  16:30:19  ECS registered
  16:31     4 of 5 FASTERQ_DUMP jobs RUNNING

Total worker-boot-to-first-job ~3 min, vs >18 hours of cyclical
spot reclamation before. Run is unblocked.

